%N A392288 Nonsquarefree numbers whose canonical prime factorization has at least two prime power factors with equal exponents.
%C A392288 Nonsquarefree terms in A130092; intersection of A013929 and A130092.
%C A392288 Superset of A303606.
%C A392288 Smallest a(n) with m distinct prime factors is 36 for m = 2, and 2*A002110(m) for m > 2.
%H A392288 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A392288/b392288.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A392288 Let s = A126706.
%e A392288 Table of n, a(n) for select n:
%e A392288       n                    a(n)
%e A392288 ---------------------------------------------------------
%e A392288       1         s(6) =      36 = 2^2 * 3^2
%e A392288       2        s(15) =      60 = 2^2 * 3   * 5
%e A392288       3        s(22) =      84 = 2^2 * 3   * 7
%e A392288       4        s(24) =      90 = 2   * 3^2 * 5
%e A392288       5        s(29) =     100 = 2^2 * 5^2
%e A392288      19        s(72) =     225 = 3^2 * 5^2
%e A392288      47       s(145) =     420 = 2^2 * 3   * 5   * 7
%e A392288     306       s(675) =    1800 = 2^3 * 3^2 * 5^2
%e A392288     698      s(1370) =    3600 = 2^4 * 3^2 * 5^2
%e A392288     929      s(1769) =    4620 = 2^2 * 3   * 5   * 7 * 11
%e A392288 1004235   s(1269950) = 3240000 = 2^6 * 3^4 * 5^4
%t A392288 Select[Range[500], (s = FactorInteger[#][[;; , -1]]; And[Length[s] > 1, Union[s] != {1}, ! DuplicateFreeQ[s] ]) &]
